ce:section.ce:para:
Chitosan has been demonstrated to temporarily break down epithelial tight junctions, enabling hydrophilic substances like insulin to pass through (Yeh et al., 2011; Sonaje et al., 2011). Desmosomes, adherent junctions, and tight junctions are the intercellular connections that epithelial cells exploit to establish an efficient barrier of defense. Between epithelial and endothelial cells are tight junctions, which are made up of a set of proteins that serve to keep organs stable and locked off from the outside environment (Lee et al., 2018). One frequent indicator of tight connection integrity is a shift in transepithelial electrical resistance. Internal and external components of tight junction proteins permit communication between cells and the active transit of liquids and small particles (Bhat et al., 2019; Wang et al., 2017). The tight junctions in the intestines serve a key role in defending against unwanted stressors, such as illnesses and inflammation. The hydrogel that is formed when carboxymethyl chitosan is combined with chitosan NPs makes it simpler to inject insulin through the intestinal lining. In vivo, the NPs successfully released insulin into the digestive environment without having a detrimental influence on the stomach. A reversible loosening of tight junctions in Caco-2 cells was also seen following chitosan-induced displacement of claudin-4 from the cell membranes to the cytoplasm (Wang et al., 2017). Therefore, it is evident that chitosan can penetrate tight junctions in a variety of ways. The process of drug delivery using GC or GME-TPP microspheres for mitochondria targeting. The drug-loaded microspheres enter the cell via endocytosis, forming endosomes. After escaping the endosome, the drug is released and directed to the mitochondria, where it accumulates to exert its therapeutic effects as shown in Fig. 5
                         (Table 1
                        ).
